<TEXT>
<P>
 THE QUEEN'S THROAT: Opera, Homosexuality and the Mystery of Desire by Wayne 
Koestenbaum (Vintage: $12; 271 pp., illustrated). Koestenbaum's idiosyncratic 
view of opera, gay subculture and diva worship takes the form of a series of 
apercus he deals out like hands in a bizarre game of Old Maid: "The opera queen 
is lonely because he listens to opera: opera isolates him from the sexual 
marketplace." His thesis is interesting, if moot, as he fails to distinguish 
between "opera queens" and people who listen to Callas CDs, not because they 
identify with her flamboyant on and off stage personae, but because they enjoy 
the beauties of the music. An odd choice for a National Book Award nomination. 
</P>
