<HEADLINE>
<P>
HAWAII GUN BUYERS HURRY TO BEAT BAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A move in the Hawaii Legislature to impose a strict ban on firearms has 
generated a surge in gun sales. 
</P>
<P>
 Police had 68 requests, or about twice as many as usual, for firearms permits 
Thursday, the day after the proposed ban was approved by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
 Gun retailers said their stores were filled with buyers and browsers and they 
expect even more business if the legislation passes the House. 
</P>
<P>
 The Senate approved a bill that would ban the import, sale or transfer of any 
handgun in Hawaii and another measure that would require the registration of 
all firearms. Currently, rifles and shotguns purchased in Hawaii do not have to 
be registered. 
</P>
<P>
 House Speaker Joseph Souki said the House will act on gun control but probably 
will approve less-restrictive measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
