<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; WASHINGTON, D.C.; IRS FLUNKS AN AUDIT -- BUT IT HAS EXCUSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The General Accounting Office, in its first-ever audit of the Internal Revenue 
Service, found "fundamental deficiencies" -- including double payment for some 
services -- in IRS management of its $6.7-billion budget in 1992. According to 
the GAO, an arm of Congress, the IRS system for administering its own money was 
so bad that auditors were unable even to review 64% of the agency's 
budget.However, the audit was performed while the IRS was in the midst of 
replacing its accounting system. "In some ways this is old news," said IRS 
Chief Financial Officer Morgan Kinghorn. "We now have . . . (the new system) in 
place. It's nearly 90% complete and it will, over time, eliminate every 
problem" cited by the GAO. The IRS is the nation's largest revenue collector, 
expecting to process tax returns from 117 million Americans this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA022094-0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 015751 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
February 20, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 27; Column 1; National Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
111 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; TENNESSEE; JUDGE RELENTS, JAILS RAPE SUSPECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A judge in Chattanooga, Tenn., who released a rape suspect last week saying he 
should get a girlfriend, reconsidered and had the man jailed.Vincent Cousin was 
ordered held pending a March 9 hearing after dozens of people called to 
complain, Judge Doug Meyer said. Cousin was arrested on a rape charge in 1989 
but was found innocent by reason of insanity. When he stopped taking medication 
and undergoing court-ordered counseling, Cousin was called dangerous by a 
mental health worker who wrote to Meyer urging that Cousin be locked up. Cousin 
was arrested Feb. 11. Prosecutors had asked Meyer to commit him to a mental 
institution, but the judge refused. 
</P>
</TEXT>
